ns can be used to improve the performance of SRSs.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe key gaps identified in the introduction revolve around the lack of established criteria for assessing sequential patterns in datasets and the need for a comprehensive approach to dataset selection and evaluation for SRSs. Potential research ideas include developing comprehensive evaluation criteria, enhancing dataset selection methods, creating automated tools for dataset analysis, and exploring the use of cross-domain datasets.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nIn the field of Machine Learning, particularly in Sequential Recommender Systems (SRSs), the evaluation of models heavily depends on the quality and suitability of the datasets used. However, there is a lack of established criteria to assess the strength of sequential patterns in these datasets, leading to potential mismatches between the datasets and the tasks they are meant to evaluate.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nWhat are the criteria for assessing the strength of sequential patterns in datasets used for evaluating Sequential Recommender Systems (SRSs)?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nEstablishing criteria for assessing sequential patterns in datasets is crucial for ensuring that SRSs are evaluated on appropriate data, which can lead to more accurate and reliable models. This research will advance the field by providing a standardized approach to dataset evaluation, improving the robustness and effectiveness of SRSs.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nDeveloping criteria for assessing sequential patterns is challenging due to the complexity and variability of user interactions across different datasets. Naive approaches may fail to capture the nuances of sequential behavior, leading to inaccurate assessments. Technical challenges include designing metrics that ca